courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of this course, students should be able to:
• review critically the food regulations and relevant national and international standards for chemical testing of food;
• identify and compare the principles and techniques used in the chemical analysis of food;
• evaluate the analytical requirement and apply the appropriate method in food analysis
• develop and implement a food safety management system and review the conformity in accordance with the relevant international standards

courses.course_syllabus:
The course covers
a) Local and relevant international regulations on food safety and quality;
b) The principles and approaches to the chemical analysis of nutrients, food additives, trace residues, contaminants and deterioration;
c) Evaluation and adoption of analytical methods for food analysis;
d) Certification requirements of food safety management system.

courses.learning_outcomes:
• Understand the basic concepts, methodologies and major techniques required for environmental analysis and monitoring;

• Able to select and apply sampling and analytical techniques for measurement of major chemical pollutants in different matrices;

• Understand the importance and development of environmental analysis and monitoring;

• Know the implementation of quality assurance and requirements for accreditation of the test methods in environmental analysis and monitoring; and

• Know the environmental laws and regulations and requirements for their compliance.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:
- Understand the principle and instrumentation of atomic absorption spectrometry;
- Understand the principle of inductively coupled plasma technology and its development in atomic emission spectrometry and mass spectrometry;
- Understand the principle and instrumentation of x-ray fluorescence spectrometry;
- Perform quantitative analysis using absorption spectrometry, plasma related spectrometry and fluorescence spectrometry
- Applications of analytical spectrometry in specific areas.

courses.course_syllabus:
The course covers
a) The Metre Convention, the International Committee for Weights and Measures Mutual Recognition Arrangement (CIPM MRA);
b) The International System of Units (SI);
c) Traceability and comparability in chemical measurements;
d) Inter-laboratory comparisons;
e) Production and use of reference materials;
f) Legal metrology and OIML International Recommendations.

courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of this course, students should be able to:
- Review critically relevant national and international standards for chemical testing of various consumer products;
- Identify and compare the compliance requirements for consumer products of major economies and appraise the attestation of test results for compliance;
- Understand and apply different extraction/digestion techniques and analytical procedures to conduct chemical testing of consumer products;
- Evaluate the toxicological risk of ingredients in various consumer products.

After completing this course, students should be able to:
a) Understand the basic methodologies and techniques of physical and chemical testing and analysis of different kinds of coatings in various products;
b) Appreciate the significance of and rationale for coating testing and analysis;
c) Select and apply sampling and analytical standards to support the assessment of quality, grading and compliance of surface finished products;
d) Understand and implement the requirements for accreditation of the test methods; and
e) Understand legislation and standards and their compliance.
